						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Conference-Proceedings-Impact-of-and-Adaptation-to-Climate-Change-in-relation-to-Food-Security-in-Africa" title="Conference Proceedings - Impact of and Adaptation to Climate Change in relation to Food Security in Africa " alt="link">Conference Proceedings - Impact of and Adaptation to Climate Change in relation to Food Security in Africa </a></h2>

	
					<p>This conference was the first of two scientific conferences planned through the cooperation between the Network of African Science Academies (NASAC) and the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Science (KNAW) aimed at assisting African academies in scientific capacity enhancement. The conference brought together the very best climate change scientists to exchange ideas and experiences on climate change impacts and adaptation in relation to food security in Africa. This issue was addressed through three critical questions on: (1) Impact: What are the impacts on food security? (2) Adaptation: What are priority adaptation measures that are needed? (3) Intervention: What interventions are needed from policy makers, decision makers, the scientific community and other stakeholders? The conference proceedings are available on the <a href="http://www.nasaconline.org/news-and-events/28-impact-of-and-adaptation-to-climate-change-in-relation-to-food-security-in-africa" target="_blank">link</a> provided. </p>
							<p><span class="date">10/04/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Conference-Proceedings-Impact-of-and-Adaptation-to-Climate-Change-in-relation-to-Food-Security-in-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Climate-change-and-agriculture-in-Africa-Analysis-of-knowledge-gaps-and-needs" title="Climate change and agriculture in Africa – Analysis of knowledge gaps and needs" alt="link">Climate change and agriculture in Africa – Analysis of knowledge gaps and needs</a></h2>

	
					<p><i>UN Economic Commission for Africa, African Climate Policy Centre, Working Paper No.7. November 2011.</i>This <a href="http://www.uneca.org/acpc/about_acpc/policy_documents/papers/WP7%20_Agriculture%20and%20Climate%20Change.pdf " target="_blank">paper</a> assesses the vulnerability of the agricultural sector in Africa to the short term climate variability and long term effects of climate change. The nexus between agricultural policy and research and development in climate variability and climate change is also explored to identify existing knowledge gaps that prevent agricultural policy development from integrating climate variability and climate change information. The study concludes by making some recommendations vis-à-vis the role of African agriculture in international climate change negotiations.</p>
							<p><span class="date">14/03/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Climate-change-and-agriculture-in-Africa-Analysis-of-knowledge-gaps-and-needs">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Climate-science-information-and-services-in-Africa-Status-gaps-and-policy-implications" title="Climate science, information, and services in Africa: Status, gaps and policy implications" alt="link">Climate science, information, and services in Africa: Status, gaps and policy implications</a></h2>

	
					<p><i>UN Economic Commission for Africa, African Climate Policy Centre, Working Paper No.1. November 2011.</i>This <a href="http://www.uneca.org/acpc/about_acpc/policy_documents/papers/WP1-climate%20Science%20data%20and%20info%20formated%20draft%20final.pdf " target="_blank">paper</a> is the result of African Climate Policy Center (ACPC) of the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (UNECA) under the Climate for Development in Africa (ClimDev Africa) programme. This paper provides an assessment of the current state of climate science, data and information in Africa and its use in development activities. It identifies key gaps and recommends actions needed to be taken for bridging the gaps. Noted gaps include the lack of provision and use of climate information and services and proposed solutions see more meteorologists being trained and better equipped weather stations.</p>
							<p><span class="date">14/03/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Climate-science-information-and-services-in-Africa-Status-gaps-and-policy-implications">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Vulnerability-of-tropical-Pacific-fisheries-and-aquaculture-to-climate-change" title="Vulnerability of tropical Pacific fisheries and aquaculture to climate change" alt="link">Vulnerability of tropical Pacific fisheries and aquaculture to climate change</a></h2>

	
					<p>The Secretariat of the Pacific Community (SPC) has released an e-book analysing the vulnerability of Pacific fisheries to climate change which includes contributions from 88 international scientists and fisheries specialists. The book was launched on the sidelines of the seventh Conference of the Pacific Community, which convened from 7 – 8 November 2011, in Noumea, New Caledonia. It predicts that ocean acidification and loss of important habitats, such as coral reefs, seagrass beds, mangroves and intertidal flats, will dramatically decrease the fish and shellfish that support many coastal communities. Communities are instead predicted to become more reliant on rich tuna resources. Freshwater fisheries are predicted to be 'winners' with the book outlining expected improvements in freshwater pond aquaculture. However, the publication notes that improved aquaculture will not be able to feed the rapidly increasing population.</p>
							<p><span class="date">14/03/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Vulnerability-of-tropical-Pacific-fisheries-and-aquaculture-to-climate-change">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Climate-Analogues-Finding-tomorrow-s-agriculture-today" title="Climate Analogues: Finding tomorrow’s agriculture today" alt="link">Climate Analogues: Finding tomorrow’s agriculture today</a></h2>

	
					<p><i>CGIAR Research Program on Climate Change, Agriculture and Food Security (CCAFS). Working Paper no. 12. 2011.</i>The analogues approach connects sites with statistically similar (‘analogous’) climates, across space (i.e. between locations) and/or time (i.e. with past or future climates). A CCAFS dissimilarity index or Hallegatte index can be used to systematically identify climate analogues across the world, for certain regions, or among specific locations. Users may use default criteria or choose from a variety of global climate models (GCMs), scenarios, and input data. Once analogue sites are identified, information gathered from local field studies or databases can be used and compared to provide data for further studies, propose high-potential adaptation pathways, facilitate farmer-to-farmer exchange of knowledge, validate computational models, test new technologies and/or techniques, or enable us to learn from history. Users may manipulate the tool in the free, open-source R software, or access a simplified user-friendly version online.<a href="http://ccafs.cgiar.org/sites/default/files/assets/docs/ccafs-wp-12-climate-analogues-web.pdf" target="_self">http://ccafs.cgiar.org/sites/default/files/assets/docs/ccafs-wp-12-climate-analogues-web.pdf</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">9/03/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Climate-Analogues-Finding-tomorrow-s-agriculture-today">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Farmers-perception-and-adaptation-to-climate-change-An-estimation-of-willingness-to-pay" title="Farmers’ perception and adaptation to climate change: An estimation of willingness to pay " alt="link">Farmers’ perception and adaptation to climate change: An estimation of willingness to pay </a></h2>

	
					<p><i>H. Acquah and E. Onumah. AGRIS on-line Papers in Economics and Informatics, Volume 3, No. 4. 2011.</i>This paper assesses farmers’ perception and adaptation to climate change to enhance policy towards tackling the challenges climate change poses to the farmers in Ghana. With regards to farmers’ perception and methods of adaptation, a majority of the farmers perceived increase in temperature and decrease in rainfall pattern. Farmers’ level of adaptation was found to be relatively high with the majority of the farmers changing planting dates and, using different crop varieties, soil conservation and water harvesting techniques as the major adaptation measures to climate change impacts. However, access to water, high cost of adaptation, lack of information, lack of knowledge on adaptation, insecure property rights, insufficient access to inputs and lack of credit were identified as the major barriers to adaptation. Results indicated that the probability of willingness to pay for climate change mitigation policies increases with age, years of education and ownership of farm land. </p>
							<p><span class="date">9/03/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Farmers-perception-and-adaptation-to-climate-change-An-estimation-of-willingness-to-pay">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Adapting-agriculture-to-climate-change" title="Adapting agriculture to climate change" alt="link">Adapting agriculture to climate change</a></h2>

	
					<p><i>A. Iglesias et al. Economía Agraria y Recursos Naturales, Volume 11, No. 2. 2011.</i>This paper evaluates the potential impacts and measures the potential limits of adaptation of agriculture to climate change. Pressures on land and water resources are expected to intensify existing risks in low latitude areas – e.g., South-East Asia deltas – and in regions with current water scarcity – e.g. Mediterranean, and create new opportunities in some northern temperate areas – e.g., Northern Russia, Northern Europe. The need to respond to these risks and opportunities is addressed by evaluating the costs and benefits of a number of technical and policy actions. The discussion aims to assist stakeholders facing the adaptation challenge and develop measures to reduce the vulnerability of the sector to climate change.</p>
							<p><span class="date">9/03/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Adapting-agriculture-to-climate-change">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Outcome-statement-from-the-First-Annual-Conference-on-Climate-Change-and-Development-in-Africa" title="Outcome statement from the First Annual Conference on Climate Change and Development in Africa" alt="link">Outcome statement from the First Annual Conference on Climate Change and Development in Africa</a></h2>

	
					<p>The first conference on Climate Change and Development in Africa (CCDA-I-I) was held from 17 - 19 October 2011 at the United Nations Conference Centre in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. The conference was jointly organized by the Climate for Development in Africa (ClimDev Africa) partners including the African Union Commission (AUC), the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and the African Development Bank (AfDB), supported by the United Nations. The outcome report states the recommendations drafted for themes like Climate Resilient Development and Adaptation and Climate Science, Data, Information and Service Delivery.<a href="http://www.uneca.org/acpc/ccda/ccda1/docs/Outcome%20Statement_ENG.pdf" target="_self">http://www.uneca.org/acpc/ccda/ccda1/docs/Outcome%20Statement_ENG.pdf</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">9/03/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Outcome-statement-from-the-First-Annual-Conference-on-Climate-Change-and-Development-in-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Climate-change-mitigations-and-agriculture" title="Climate change mitigations and agriculture " alt="link">Climate change mitigations and agriculture </a></h2>

	
					<p>The book focuses on design and practical implementation of mitigation activities through changing farming systems rather than the science of emissions reduction which is well covered in most publications. It identifies the feasibility, opportunities and challenges for achieving mitigation among smallholder farmers. Aimed at accelerating efforts towards mitigating land-based climate change. While much attention has been focused on forestry for its reputed cost-effectiveness, the agricultural sector contributes about ten to twelve per cent of emissions and has a large technical and economic potential for reducing greenhouse gases. (Via <a href="http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/123199/" target="_blank">ICTSD</a>)</p>
							<p><span class="date">28/02/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Climate-change-mitigations-and-agriculture">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Agricultural-Development-under-a-Changing-Climate-Opportunities-and-Challenges-for-Adaptation" title="Agricultural Development under a Changing Climate: Opportunities and Challenges for Adaptation" alt="link">Agricultural Development under a Changing Climate: Opportunities and Challenges for Adaptation</a></h2>

	
					<p>This report reviews the major effects of climate change on the agricultural sector. It examines the causes of vulnerability and suggests a range of potential options and investment opportunities for supporting adaptation efforts and building adaptive capacity. This report primarily focuses on appropriate strategies for adapting to climate change impacts that are projected to occur over the next one to two decades, although several issues covered in this report are important for long-term adaptation needs as well. This report also describes opportunities for linking adaptation and mitigation, and it discusses the importance of mainstreaming adaptation into development.</p>
							<p><span class="date">12/01/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Climate-change/Relevant-publications/Agricultural-Development-under-a-Changing-Climate-Opportunities-and-Challenges-for-Adaptation">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl" />
<p>

